column8:
After it opened its doors to the congregation in 1922, the Pilgrim Baptist Church quickly became known as the birthplace of gospel music under the leadership of music director Thomas Dorsey (also known as the Father of Gospel Music) who remained in that position for decades. Dorsey would compose thousands of songs and arrangements over his lifetime, but he is perhaps most famous for the song Take My Hand, Precious Lord, which he wrote after the death of his wife.

Just as the genre of the blues, however, was inextricably formed and shaped by its more spiritual sister, gospel can trace its roots back to a deeply-intertwined relationship with the blues as well. Before Dorsey was the Father of Gospel, he was a bluesman in Georgia -- and then a bluesman in Chicago.

He performed under the moniker 'Georgia Tom' with similarly-named Tampa Red, and as a part of this collaboration the two of them released It's Tight Like That, one of the songs that kicked off the hokum genre. However, Dorsey ultimately quit the blues in favor of focusing his musical efforts on gospel. Under his direction, Pilgrim Baptist Church became host to a whole generation of gospel greats including--most notably--Mahalia Jackson.

column8: The Regal Theater was well-known for being Chicago's premiere entertainment venue that catered primarily to African Americans. Renown musicians such as Cab Calloway and Louis Armstrong performed here. The theater featured live music shows, film showings, and live stage shows. column3: Swingland Café (later known as The Rhumboogie)
column8:
By 1936, 343 E 55th had become a nightclub space that would operate off-and-on as the Swingland Café (or Dave's, depending which of its three owners was currently in charge). In April of 1942, however, it opened its doors as the Rhumboogie Café under the ownership of Charlie Glenn boxing legend Joe Louis.

Although tremendously influential throughout its lifespan, the Rhumboogie didn't last long -- New Year's Eve of 1945 would be the end of the club's heyday as a stray cigarette started a fire. Although it reopened that June, it never regained its status or momentum and closed forever in 1947.

T-Bone Walker was one of the musicians perhaps most associated with the Rhumboogie: he had numerous stays as an artist there, and even recorded music under the short-lived Rhumboogie Label. Walker had made his early career in Los Angeles, but came to Chicago for a contract with the Rhumboogie that catapulted the club to legendary status. (was also a black and tan? -connor)

column8: This was a very well-known club. Opened by Theresa Needham in 1949 and known for its high caliber music scene, the tavern was a beloved neighborhood establishment. It featured live music shows Friday through Monday and 'Blues Mondays', where the most well-known blues musicians would come and hang around while Junior Wells and his band played music. Buddy Guy and Junior Wells gained popularity here and were talked into producing Hoodoo Man Blues, which would launch their careers. Theresa Needham was inducted into the Blues Foundation Hall of Fame.

column8: The Tivoli Theater was opened in 1921 and could accomodate nearly 5000 patrons. The theater was described as beging very elegant and ornate. It featured a marble interior, crystal lighting throughout, and air-conditioning. The theater drew nearly 7000 people every weekend and it began hosting live music shows in 1959.

column8: The ballroom was known for its lavish decor and its enforcement of decency and social ettiquette, and it was called "America's most luxurious public ballroom". The club was whites-only until the 1950s, after which it opened up to allow everyone and began billing musicians like Muddy Waters, Buddy Guy, and Bo Diddley.
